  "opinion": "As a man in his late sixties who grew up in a small Italian town and now lives in Lecce, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can shape a person's path. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a psychological term—it's the weight of expectations that can make someone feel like they're failing before they even start. When I was a young man studying engineering in the 1960s, the idea of women or people from minority backgrounds even thinking about pursuing science was almost unheard of. Today, the same thing happens with students from immigrant families or those who don't fit the traditional mold of a 'STEM person.' The anxiety that comes from knowing you're being judged by a stereotype can be paralyzing. I've experienced this myself as someone who's anxious about making mistakes, especially in situations where I feel like I'm not 'meant' to be in this field. But addressing it isn't about fixing people—it's about creating spaces where everyone feels safe to try. In my community, where I've spent most of my life watching others struggle, I've seen how simple things like encouraging a child to ask questions, or making sure teachers understand the cultural backgrounds of their students, can make a huge difference. We need to shift from 'this is how it's supposed to be' to 'this is how we can all grow together.' It's not about changing who we are but about changing how we see ourselves in the world.",
